tem\",\"subtype\":\"stop_hook_summary\",\"hookCount\":1,\"hookInfos\":[{\"command\":\"go run ${CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR}/cmd/entire/main.go hooks claude-code stop\",\"durationMs\":933}],\"hookErrors\":[],\"preventedContinuation\":false,\"stopReason\":\"\",\"hasOutput\":false,\"level\":\"suggestion\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-06T22:31:50.747Z\",\"uuid\":\"7fc1ef57-5f84-4fdc-bb09-ff3e76d9420b\",\"toolUseID\":\"832ebaba-d1b9-4f70-bae8-3506c7696f43\"}\n{\"type\":\"queue-operation\",\"operation\":\"enqueue\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-06T22:34:23.124Z\",\"sessionId\":\"0fda4de8-f2b5-487d-a677-e9891c0c4f83\",\"content\":\"<task-notification>\\n<task-id>a729ee46dd77d7b66</task-id>\\n<tool-use-id>toolu_01AKqCpK8ZUYZq1CQqGXaxy5</tool-use-id>\\n<status>completed</status>\\n<summary>Agent \\\"Type design analysis\\\" completed</summary>\\n<result>I now have all the information needed for a comprehensive type design review. Let me compile my analysis.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Type Design Analysis: `post-file-edit-gemini` branch\\n\\nThis analysis covers new and modified types introduced in the PR, focusing on invariant quality, encapsulation, and practical value.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Type: `EventType` (modified) -- `FileEdit` constant\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/agent/event.go`\\n\\n### Invariants Identified\\n- `EventType` is a closed set of lifecycle events (`iota + 1` through `FileEdit`)\\n- Zero value is intentionally invalid (iota starts at 1)\\n- Every `EventType` must have a corresponding `String()` case\\n- Every `EventType` must have a corresponding dispatcher case in `DispatchLifecycleEvent`\\n\\n### Ratings\\n- **Encapsulation**: 6/10\\n  The type is `int`-based, meaning any int can be cast to `EventType`. This is standard Go practice for iota enums and is acceptable given that the `default` arm in `DispatchLifecycleEvent` returns an error for unknown types. The real enforcement boundary is the dispatcher, not the type itself.\\n\\n- **Invariant Expression**: 7/10\\n  The new `FileEdit` constant is appended at the end of the iota sequence, preserving backward-compatible wire values for all existing constants. The `String()` method and dispatcher both handle it. The comment on the constant clearly explains its purpose and the framework's expected behavior (appending to tracking file).\\n\\n- **Invariant Usefulness**: 8/10\\n  `FileEdit` fills a genuine gap: before this PR, file tracking required transcript parsing at commit time, which is expensive and error-prone. Making it an explicit lifecycle event allows real-time incremental tracking. The event type clearly distinguishes \\\"file was modified\\\" from all other lifecycle phases.\\n\\n- **Invariant Enforcement**: 6/10\\n  No enforcement that `FileEdit` events must have a non-empty `FilePath`. The dispatcher in `handleLifecycleFileEdit` handles this gracefully (returns nil), but the type itself allows construction of `FileEdit` events with empty `FilePath`. This is a pragmatic tradeoff -- see Concerns below.\\n\\n### Strengths\\n- Clean extension of the existing enum pattern\\n- iota ordering is backward-compatible (new constant appended at the end)\\n- String() method and dispatcher are both updated in lockstep\\n\\n### Concerns\\n- The `Event` struct is a flat \\\"god struct\\\" with fields that are only relevant for specific event types (`FilePath` for `FileEdit`, `ToolUseID` for subagent events, `Prompt` for `TurnStart`, etc.). This is a pre-existing design issue that this PR does not worsen significantly by adding one more field.\\n- There is no compile-time enforcement that a `FileEdit` event has a `FilePath`. A discriminated union or sealed interface would express this more strongly, but that would be a large architectural change inconsistent with the codebase's established patterns.\\n\\n### Recommended Improvements\\nNone for this PR. The flat-struct approach is a conscious tradeoff in this codebase, and adding one more field does not cross a complexity threshold that would justify refactoring the Event type.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Type: `Event.FilePath` (new field)\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/agent/event.go`, line 123-126\\n\\n### Invariants Identified\\n- Should be populated only for `FileEdit` events\\n- May be absolute or relative; the framework normalizes before persisting\\n- Must not contain newline characters (enforced downstream in `AppendFileTouched`)\\n\\n### Ratings\\n- **Encapsulation**: 5/10\\n  The field is public and writable by anyone constructing an `Event`. No protection against setting `FilePath` on a non-`FileEdit` event. This matches the pattern of every other field on `Event`.\\n\\n- **Invariant Expression**: 7/10\\n  The doc comment clearly states it is \\\"for FileEdit events\\\" and that it \\\"may be absolute -- the framework normalizes to repo-relative before persisting.\\\" This is sufficient documentation given the codebase conventions.\\n\\n- **Invariant Usefulness**: 8/10\\n  Carries exactly the information the framework needs for incremental file tracking. The single-file-per-event model aligns with how Write/Edit tools operate (one file per invocation).\\n\\n- **Invariant Enforcement**: 5/10\\n  Normalization (absolute to repo-relative) and validation (no newlines, must be within repo) happen in `handleLifecycleFileEdit`, not at construction time. This is appropriate given the design: the `Event` is constructed in agent-specific code, and the framework is the consumer that does normalization.\\n\\n### Strengths\\n- Clean separation: agents populate raw paths, framework normalizes\\n- Comment explains the normalization contract explicitly\\n- Single-file design correctly models the Write/Edit tool semantics\\n\\n### Concerns\\n- None significant beyond the general flat-struct concern noted above.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Type: `afterToolHookInputRaw` (new)\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/agent/geminicli/types.go`, lines 78-85\\n\\n### Invariants Identified\\n- `SessionID` and `TranscriptPath` are required for lifecycle routing\\n- `ToolName` identifies which tool executed\\n- `ToolInput` is `json.RawMessage` to allow deferred parsing based on tool type\\n\\n### Ratings\\n- **Encapsulation**: 6/10\\n  Unexported type (lowercase `a`), which correctly restricts it to the `geminicli` package. Fields are public for JSON deserialization, which is a Go necessity.\\n\\n- **Invariant Expression**: 7/10\\n  `json.RawMessage` for `ToolInput` is the right choice -- it defers parsing to the consumer, which knows the expected schema. This avoids coupling the hook input type to any specific tool's input format. The doc comment explains the provenance clearly.\\n\\n- **Invariant Usefulness**: 8/10\\n  This type fills a real need. Previously there was no Gemini type for AfterTool hook payloads containing tool details. The `ToolName` and `ToolInput` fields enable the new file-edit parsing without modifying the existing `sessionInfoRaw` or `agentHookInputRaw` types (which don't carry tool information).\\n\\n- **Invariant Enforcement**: 5/10\\n  No validation that required fields are non-empty. This is consistent with all other `*Raw` types in this package -- they are deserialization targets, and validation happens in the parsing functions that consume them. The `parseFileEdit` method handles empty/missing fields gracefully.\\n\\n### Strengths\\n- Follows the established `*Raw` naming convention for deserialization-only types\\n- Package-private visibility\\n- `json.RawMessage` for polymorphic tool input is the standard Go approach\\n- Clear doc comment connecting it to Gemini CLI's AfterTool hooks\\n\\n### Concerns\\n- None. This is a well-crafted internal DTO.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Type: `fileEditToolInput` (new, two versions)\\n\\n**Files:**\\n- `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/agent/geminicli/lifecycle.go`, lines 185-189\\n- `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/agent/claudecode/lifecycle.go`, lines 191-193\\n\\n### Invariants Identified\\n- Claude version: only `FilePath` field (Claude Write/Edit always use `file_path`)\\n- Gemini version: three fields (`FilePath`, `Path`, `Filename`) with a priority order\\n- The `filePath()` method on the Gemini version encodes the fallback chain\\n\\n### Ratings\\n- **Encapsulation**: 6/10\\n  Both are unexported types, correctly scoped to their packages. The Gemini version has a method that encapsulates the priority logic.\\n\\n- **Invariant Expression**: 7/10\\n  The Gemini version's `filePath()` method clearly encodes the fallback chain: `file_path > path > filename`. The doc comment on the struct explains why three fields exist (\\\"Gemini tools use file_path, path, or filename depending on the tool\\\"). The Claude version is simpler because Claude consistently uses `file_path`.\\n\\n- **Invariant Usefulness**: 8/10\\n  Both types solve the practical problem of extracting a file path from heterogeneous tool input JSON. The Gemini version handles real-world variance across four different tools.\\n\\n- **Invariant Enforcement**: 6/10\\n  The `filePath()` method returns empty string when all fields are empty, and callers check for this. This is a clean, sufficient design.\\n\\n### Strengths\\n- Appropriate divergence between Claude (simple) and Gemini (fallback chain)\\n- The `filePath()` helper method encapsulates the resolution logic\\n- Both types are package-private DTOs used only for JSON deserialization\\n\\n### Concerns\\n- **Name collision**: Both packages define a type named `fileEditToolInput`. This is fine because they are in separate packages, but it creates a mild readability concern when reading the diff. Since they have genuinely different structures (one field vs. three), merging them into a shared type in the `agent` package would be wrong -- they model different agent contracts. The name collision is acceptable.\\n- The Gemini `filePath()` method uses a value receiver, which is idiomatic for a small struct. No issue here.\\n\\n### Recommended Improvements\\nNone. The two types correctly model their respective agents' contracts and are appropriately scoped.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Type: `PostFileEditInput` (new, integration test)\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/integration_test/hooks.go`, lines 409-415\\n\\n### Invariants Identified\\n- Test helper DTO for simulating post-file-edit hooks\\n- Fields mirror the Claude Code PostToolUse hook payload structure\\n\\n### Ratings\\n- **Encapsulation**: 6/10\\n  Public fields for test construction. Appropriate for a test helper.\\n\\n- **Invariant Expression**: 6/10\\n  Clear, simple struct. No validation needed for a test input type.\\n\\n- **Invariant Usefulness**: 7/10\\n  Necessary to test the file-edit flow end-to-end. Follows the existing pattern of `PostTodoInput` and similar test input types.\\n\\n- **Invariant Enforcement**: N/A\\n  Test infrastructure types do not need enforcement.\\n\\n### Strengths\\n- Consistent with existing `PostTodoInput` pattern\\n- Both `HookRunner.SimulatePostFileEdit` and `TestEnv.SimulatePostFileEdit` convenience methods provided\\n\\n### Concerns\\n- None.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Type: `StateStore` (modified) -- new `AppendFileTouched` / `ReadFilesTouched` / `ClearFilesTouched` methods\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/session/state.go`, lines 412-502\\n\\n### Invariants Identified\\n1. Session ID must pass `validation.ValidateSessionID` (prevents path traversal)\\n2. File paths must not contain `\\\\n` or `\\\\r` (prevents line injection in the append-only format)\\n3. The `.files` tracking file uses one-path-per-line format with newline delimiters\\n4. `ReadFilesTouched` deduplicates and sorts\\n5. `ClearFilesTouched` is idempotent (no error on non-existent file)\\n6. `Clear()` already uses a glob (`sessionID+\\\".*\\\"`) to remove all session files, so `.files` is automatically cleaned up\\n\\n### Ratings\\n- **Encapsulation**: 8/10\\n  All file path manipulation is internal. The public API is `AppendFileTouched(ctx, sessionID, filePath)` -- callers don't know about the `.files` file format. The `filesTouchedPath` helper is private. The design is clean.\\n\\n- **Invariant Expression**: 8/10\\n  The line-injection guard (`strings.ContainsAny(filePath, \\\"\\\\n\\\\r\\\")`) directly protects the file format invariant. Session ID validation prevents path traversal. The deduplicate-on-read contract is clearly documented.\\n\\n- **Invariant Usefulness**: 9/10\\n  These methods solve a critical performance problem: the previous approach required parsing the full transcript at commit time to discover which files were modified. The new append-only tracking file makes this O(1) per tool invocation, with read being O(n) in files touched (which is always small). The design is intentionally lightweight -- no JSON parsing, no file locking, just `O_APPEND` writes.\\n\\n- **Invariant Enforcement**: 8/10\\n  - Session ID validated on every operation (Append, Read, Clear)\\n  - Newline injection prevented on write\\n  - Directory created with restrictive permissions (0o750)\\n  - File created with restrictive permissions (0o600)\\n  - Idempotent clear (no error on non-existent)\\n  - Existing `Clear()` method already cleans up `.files` via the `sessionID+\\\".*\\\"` glob pattern\\n\\n### Strengths\\n- The append-only write / deduplicate-on-read pattern is a smart design for this use case. It avoids any need for file locking even with concurrent tool invocations within the same session.\\n- `O_APPEND` is atomic on POSIX for writes smaller than `PIPE_BUF` (4096 bytes), so concurrent appends of file paths will not interleave.\\n- The `Clear()` glob already covers `.files` -- no separate cleanup path needed.\\n- Thorough test coverage including: deduplication, idempotent clear, session ID validation, newline injection rejection, and cleanup of `.files` alongside `.json` state.\\n\\n### Concerns\\n1. **No file locking for concurrent sessions.** Two concurrent sessions with the same session ID could write to the same `.files` file. However, the CLAUDE.md documentation indicates this is the expected behavior (\\\"both sessions can proceed -- their checkpoints interleave on the same shadow branch\\\"). The `O_APPEND` mode ensures atomic appends.\\n\\n2. **Unbounded file growth within a session.** If an agent edits the same file 10,000 times, the `.files` file grows linearly. Deduplication only happens on read. For most sessions this is negligible, but pathological cases could produce large tracking files. The `clearFilesTracking` calls at condensation/commit time bound the actual lifetime.\\n\\n3. **`strings.SplitSeq` usage in `ReadFilesTouched`.** This uses Go 1.24's iterator-based split. The project uses Go 1.25.x per CLAUDE.md, so this is fine. Just noting this as a newer API that may surprise readers.\\n\\n### Recommended Improvements\\nNone for this PR. The append-only pattern is the right tradeoff for a hot path (called on every file edit). The unbounded growth concern is mitigated by the clearing at commit time.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Type: `FileModificationTools` (modified, Gemini CLI)\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/agent/geminicli/types.go`, lines 98-104\\n\\n### Invariants Identified\\n- Lists all Gemini CLI tool names that modify files\\n- Used both for hook installation (AfterTool matchers) and for transcript analysis\\n- Must be kept in sync with Gemini CLI's actual tool naming\\n\\n### Ratings\\n- **Encapsulation**: 5/10\\n  Public `var` (mutable slice). Any consumer could mutate it at runtime. This is a pre-existing issue -- the slice was exported before this PR.\\n\\n- **Invariant Expression**: 7/10\\n  The associated `Tool*` constants (`ToolWriteFile`, `ToolEditFile`, `ToolSaveFile`, `ToolReplace`) clearly name each tool. The doc comment explains the naming inconsistency between internal and display names.\\n\\n- **Invariant Usefulness**: 8/10\\n  Single source of truth for file-modifying tools, reused across hook installation, transcript analysis, and now hook-based file tracking.\\n\\n- **Invariant Enforcement**: 4/10\\n  Being a mutable exported `var`, it can be modified at runtime. This is low-risk in practice since it is never mutated after initialization, but technically violates immutability principles.\\n\\n### Concerns\\n- The mutable `var` export is a pre-existing pattern across all agents (Claude Code, OpenCode, FactoryAIDroid all export `FileModificationTools` the same way). This PR does not change the pattern.\\n\\n### Recommended Improvements\\nThis is outside the scope of this PR, but converting to a function (`func FileModificationTools() []string`) that returns a copy would prevent mutation. Not urgent.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Cross-cutting Analysis\\n\\n### Backward Compatibility\\n\\nThe changes are fully backward-compatible:\\n- `EventType.FileEdit` is appended at the end of the iota sequence (value 9), so all existing constants retain their values.\\n- `Event.FilePath` is a new optional field with zero value `\\\"\\\"`. Existing code that constructs `Event` values will continue to work.\\n- The `State.FilesTouched` field in session JSON is unchanged. The new `.files` tracking file is a complementary data source, and `resolveFilesTouched` merges both sources.\\n- The `Clear()` method's glob (`sessionID+\\\".*\\\"`) already covers the new `.files` extension without code changes.\\n\\n### Naming Consistency\\n\\n- `HookNamePostFileEdit = \\\"post-file-edit\\\"` is defined identically in both `claudecode` and `geminicli` packages. The comment in `hook_registry.go` (line 83: \\\"same value for all agents\\\") correctly notes this. This is a reasonable approach that avoids a shared constant while documenting the coupling.\\n- `fileEditToolInput` is defined in both packages with different structures. The name collision is acceptable because the types are package-private and model genuinely different contracts.\\n- `PostFileEditInput` in integration tests follows the established `Post*Input` naming convention.\\n- `AppendFileTouched` / `ReadFilesTouched` / `ClearFilesTouched` follow a clear CRUD naming pattern on `StateStore`.\\n\\n### Design Pattern Observations\\n\\nThe `handleLifecycleFileEdit` handler intentionally swallows all errors (returns `nil` unconditionally), logging them as warnings. This is documented and deliberate: file tracking is an optimization over transcript parsing, not a correctness requirement. If tracking fails, the fallback in `resolveFilesTouched` will still extract file information from the transcript. This layered-fallback design is sound.\\n\\nThe `resolveFilesTouched` changes in `manual_commit_hooks.go` merge three sources: `state.FilesTouched` (from the JSON session state, populated by agents that provide `ModifiedFiles` on SubagentEnd), the `.files` tracking file (from real-time hook tracking), and the transcript fallback. The merge logic deduplicates and sorts. This is a clean additive change that does not break the existing flow.\\n\\n### Summary\\n\\nThe type design in this PR is pragmatic and well-executed. New types are appropriately scoped (package-private DTOs), the `Event` extension is backward-compatible, and the `StateStore` additions have strong invariant enforcement (session ID validation, newline injection prevention, idempotent cleanup). The only structural concern is the `Event` flat-struct pattern, which is a pre-existing codebase convention that this PR does not meaningfully worsen.</result>\\n<usage><total_tokens>82043</total_tokens><tool_uses>22</tool_uses><duration_ms>185401</duration_ms></usage>\\n</task-notification>\\nFull transcript available at: /private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-alex-workspace-cli--worktrees-3/tasks/a729ee46dd77d7b66.output\"}\n{\"type\":\"queue-operation\",\"operation\":\"dequeue\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-06T22:34:23.13